AB  - Restrictions on hate speech are typically seen as rooted in the histories, politics and legal processes of particular countries. Using the case of a recently enacted Swedish law protecting sexual minorities from contemptuous speech, this article shows that there is also an important if understudied transnational dimension. International gay activists, along with their Swedish counterparts, supported both the law and an important prosecution thereunder, as part of a broader effort to promote protections for homosexuals worldwide. But the statute and prosecution also prompted vehement opposition from Christian traditionalists both within and outside Sweden. They claimed that the new law threatened their right to express their deep religious convictions against homosexuality. Intervenors on both sides sought to influence the Swedish parliament, courts and public opinion. Reciprocally, foreign activists on both sides used the Swedish case in their own domestic battles over various aspects of gay rights and religious expression. Documenting these interrelated controversies, the article demonstrates the transnational aspects of hate speech laws.
